<HL>
   Food Stamps Fail
   To Cover Needs
   Of the Rural Poor
   ----
   By Bruce Ingersoll
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/14/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<GV>
AGRICULTURE DEPARTMENT (AGD)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The nation's rural poor are going hungry
because food-stamp benefits aren't enough to cover higher
food costs in impoverished rural counties, a new consumer
survey shows.
   Public Voice for Food and Health Policy, a
Washington-based consumer group, says that of nine million
rural Americans living in poverty, many are food-stamp
recipients who are paying higher prices for fewer calories
than the poor in cities.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In its survey of 33 counties with a 25% poverty rate, the
group found that the weekly $75 food-stamp allotment for a
household of four isn't adequate to buy all of the food in
the government's "thrifty food plan," which is regarded as
the minimum diet from a nutrition standpoint. It takes $102 a
week to buy the thrifty food plan if food-stamp recipients
don't have access to competitively priced supermarkets and
must shop at higher priced mom-and-pop stores, according to
the survey.
   What's more, even at rural supermarkets, the average cost
of foods in the thrifty plan is 8% higher than the $75
allotment, the survey shows.
   Ellen Haas, executive director of Public Voice, faults the
Agriculture Department, which administers the food-stamp
program, for failing to take the urban-rural price
differences into account.
   The results of the national survey, conducted last year,
will strengthen the hand of Rep. Leon Panetta (D., Calif.)
and other lawmakers who are pushing hunger-relief measures
this year in Congress. The group also found that one of every
three food-stamp dollars in poor areas is spent in crossroads
stores and small-town grocery stores where supplies of fresh
produce and meat are limited. Last summer, 23% of the stores
surveyed didn't stock any fresh vegetables and 33% didn't
stock any fresh fruits, while 30% didn't sell fresh meats.
   In its survey, the group recommends increasing food-stamp
allotments 17% by fiscal 1995 to boost the poor's purchasing
power and re-evaluating the Agriculture Department's methods
for determining food-stamp benefits. In addition, it calls
for federal grants to help small rural stores set up
wholesale-purchasing cooperatives and become more
price-competitive with supermarkets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
