</DOCID>
<HL>
   McDonnell Douglas Warns Employees
   Its Aircraft Unit Faces Tough Times
   ----
   By Rick Wartzman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/14/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5C
</SO>
<CO>
   MD LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<LP>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. -- McDonnell Douglas Corp. executives
are stepping up their rhetoric in a bid to turn around the
company's transport aircraft facility here.
   In a letter sent to employees last week, Chairman John
McDonnell said that unless performance radically improves,
"lenders could lose confidence in the company's ability to
cover interest payments and repay the principal." In the
first quarter, the Long Beach subsidiary posted an operating
loss of $84 million, and the corporation as a whole barely
broke even.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. McDonnell said in his memo that in 1990 the company
will invest as much as $2 billion in the MD-11 commercial jet
program as it readies the three-engine craft for
certification by the Federal Aviation Administration. Coupled
with additional outlays for the troubled C-17 military cargo
plane, also built here, and several jet-fighter programs, he
indicated that the company's net cash outflow this year could
total $1.2 billion. That amount, the chairman said, must be
borrowed on top of the $2.5 billion in debt that McDonnell
Douglas had at the end of March.
   Mr. McDonnell maintained that "this higher debt level is
not necessarily a problem in itself." But he noted that "the
combination of high debt, negative cash flow and poor
performance affecting profitability does require action" that
will assuage lenders' concerns. The details of the chairman's
letter were first reported in the Orange County Register.
   The newspaper also disclosed the existence of another
document, which it described as a paraphrasing of remarks
recently made by John Capellupo, deputy president of the Long
Beach subsidiary. "The company is in big trouble," Mr.
Capellupo is quoted as saying. "If the C-17 has any more
problems; and if the MD-11 isn't certified and delivers 5-6
aircraft by the end of the year; and if the MD-80 doesn't
start producing aircraft like they are supposed to," then the
Long Beach division "could be history."
   In the wake of Lockheed Corp.'s announcement earlier this
month that it would completely pull its aircraft operations
out of Burbank, Calif., plus the memory that McDonnell
Douglas had contemplated leaving the commercial airplane
business in the early 1980s, the Capellupo comments set off
alarm bells. The Register interpreted them to mean that the
company was considering mothballing the factory here, and ran
a page-one headline that declared: "Long Beach aircraft maker
might close."
   However, McDonnell Douglas officials were quick to insist
that shuttering the plant is not even an option at this
point. "We have absolutely no plans to sell the property, no
plans to shut the doors," a spokesman at corporate
headquarters in St. Louis said.
   Doug Griffith, president of United Auto Workers local 148,
which represents nearly 20,000 McDonnell Douglas workers in
Long Beach, also asserted that there was no possibility of
closure. "That would be tantamount to the demise of the whole
corporation," he said, pointing out that McDonnell Douglas
has long set its sights on making the commercial airplane
lines here its financial backbone, thereby offsetting
slumping sales to the Pentagon.
   Nonetheless, it's clear that the pressure is mounting in
Long Beach, where 4,000 workers -- almost all white-collar --
will be laid off by the end of summer. Upper-level managers
in particular "are feeling the screws," one employee said.
   Mr. Capellupo, who along with other senior executives
declined to be interviewed, is quoted as saying: "The banks
have heard all our problems and solutions, but are about fed
up with us."
   And in his letter, Mr. McDonnell said the company has only
two undesirable alternatives besides getting planes out more
efficiently. The first would be to sell more stock to
increase equity. But that, he said, would be "very expensive
to our present shareholders because we would be issuing
shares of stock in the $40s and $50s when our net asset value
is in the $80s. That would dilute the stock that we all own."
   The second option would be to cut back commercial
transport production. That, however, "would put us even
farther behind in deliveries to our airline customers and
would quickly cause them to lose confidence in us as a
reliable supplier. That, in turn, would result in a
significant deterioration of our position in or outright
elimination from that market and could relegate us to only a
declining defense business.
   "It would," he continued, "require us to lay off up to
half" of the 50,000 workers employed at Long Beach.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900514-0123
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900514-0123.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):
   ABC's Documentary
</HL>
<DATE>
05/14/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A16
</SO>
<CO>
   CCB FREST
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   ABC's Cambodia documentary, "Peter Jennings Reporting:
From the Killing Fields" deserves some comment of its own,
insofar as it is the centerpiece of this controversy.
   It's our experience that Mr. Jennings's daily instinct is
to play the news straight. But TV journalism -- with its mix
of images, sound and facts -- is an unwieldy instrument, and
too often, large efforts, such as this documentary, go awry.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Why, we wonder (not for the first time) is there so little
room for sublety in TV news? Why is it necessary for TV
journalism to dwell forever in a world of melodramas
inhabited only by the innocent and those who scheme against
the innocent?
   The ABC documentary displayed many of the techniques TV
uses repeatedly to make sure viewers Get The Message.
   The most familiar is focusing in tight close-up on the
face of one's opponent during an interrogation, as Mr.
Jennings did repeatedly with a State Department official.
From this Joe Isuzu interview, ABC's cameras cut to pictures
of desperately ill Cambodian children (with an obligatory
close-up of a fly on a little limb) who presumably would live
happily ever after except for U.S. intransigence.
   We get old footage of the Nixon administration's Cambodian
incursion, bombs cascading down, set against footage of Kent
State going up in smoke, without the least awareness that the
incursion was intended to keep the Khmer Rouge from
prevailing. Throughout, there is withering skepticism about
U.S. explanations and motives set against bland acceptance of
false Vietnamese claims to have withdrawn from Cambodia.
   In his letter to us defending the program, Mr. Jennings
asks why (except presumably to give them arms) is a U.S.
Special Forces colonel in Khmer Rouge refugee camps? Simply,
common sense will tell you, to find out what they're up to.
   This tendentious character in what purports to be
objective reporting invites suspicion of political motives.
The political stance of the program's producer is surely
relevant, and Mr. Jennings and columnist Anthony Lewis smear
Stephen Morris with their charge of McCarthyism. Yet in the
end, we think that politics is less of an explanation than
the nature of television, which to tell the news needs black
hats and white hats.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900514-0122
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900514-0122.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Technology:
   IBM Is Expected
   To Unveil Wider
   Uses for CallPath
   ----
   By Laurence Hooper
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/14/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5
</SO>
<CO>
   IBM G.SIE NT T
</CO>
<IN>
COMMUNICATIONS TECHNOLOGY (CMT)
SOFTWARE (SOF)
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- International Business Machines Corp. is
expected to unveil tomorrow a major expansion in the
capabilities of CallPath, a software product that links
telephone switches to computers, industry executives said.
   IBM will announce CallPath support for telephone switches
other than those made by Rolm, the telecommunications concern
that it owns in partnership with Siemens AG, the executives
said. It will also announce several new CallPath features,
and will outline a set of protocols for companies that write
software that works with CallPath, they added.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   IBM declined to comment, but has scheduled a "major
telecommunications announcement" for tomorrow.
   CallPath identifies callers to a telephone switch known as
a PBX, for private branch exchange, and automatically pulls
information about them from an IBM minicomputer or mainframe.
Telephone operators -- customer service representatives or
brokers, for example -- can see callers' files displayed on a
screen as soon as they pick up the phone, which saves time
and opens up new marketing opportunities.
   Currently, CallPath works only with Rolm PBXs, and only
with incoming calls. The executives said IBM will announce
CallPath support for PBXs made by Northern Telecom Inc. and
American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co., among others. They also
said CallPath will work with outgoing calls -- a big plus for
telemarketing companies and others that depend on calling
their customers.
   AT&amp;T, Northern Telecom and Rolm together dominate the PBX
market. Since many companies keep their customer databases on
IBM computers, IBM's announcement opens up CallPath services
to a huge audience.
   In addition, the industry executives said IBM will
announce a set of standards and protocols that will enable
software writers to develop CallPath applications that work
in a large variety of environments.
   "This is going to be great news for all the different
vendors playing in this marketplace," said Dixon Doll,
chairman of DMW Group, a consulting firm in Ann Arbor, Mich.
"A very major vendor is putting a very big stake in the
ground, and everyone can take their direction from it.
Customers can now be sure that standards are going to emerge
in this market."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
