   Business Brief -- Artel Communications Corp.:
   Revenue in Second Quarter
   To Be Below Expectations
</HL>
<DATE>
05/14/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C12
</SO>
<CO>
   AXXX
</CO>
<LP>
   Artel Communications Corp. said it expects to report
second-quarter revenue that is "significantly" lower than
"might have been expected."
   Artel added that it doesn't expect to report a profit for
the quarter.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Hudson, Mass., maker of fiber optic communications
systems attributed the lower revenue to delays in U.S. and
European government programs, lower sales to Pacific Rim
customers and a longer-than-expected purchasing approval
process among some new customers.
   In the second quarter ended July 1, 1989, the company
earned $281,000, or seven cents a share, on revenue of $2.8
million.
   Artel said it has "implemented cost-containment actions
while maintaining the ongoing product development programs."
The company added that it expects to make "significant" new
product announcements by year end.
</TEXT>
