<HL>
   International -- Washington Insight:
   Whispers of a Soviet-German Concord
   Are Heard Under Kremlin's Grumbling
   ----
   By Walter S. Mossberg
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/14/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP FREST
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Despite Moscow's grumbling about reunifying
Germany, there are signs of a budding Soviet-German concord
in the wind.
   U.S. officials privately predict that the emerging
economic ties between the two countries will temper Soviet
opposition to German unification. But the Soviet Union and
Germany also are finding common ground on political and
strategic issues -- a development that could threaten
Washington's hopes of keeping Germany firmly in the Western
orbit.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The potential bond between Europe's two strongest powers
is likely to be built on an economic foundation. "The Soviets
need Germany economically," said one top Bush administration
policy-maker, who reviewed the recent opening round of
six-power talks on German unification.
   "They depended on East Germany for so much," he said, "and
they're going to need united Germany to continue that trade.
Plus they need new investment from Germany. So they're not
likely to want to be viewed as the only power blocking German
unification."
   Others agree. "The Soviet Union's largest East European
trading partner is East Germany, its largest Western trading
partner is West Germany," says Charles Gati, a specialist on
Soviet-East European affairs at Union College and author of a
new book on the subject. "So you can just imagine the
economic stakes the Soviet Union has with the new Germany."
   Adds former State Department official Robert Hormats, now
with Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co., "The economic relationship with
Germany is Gorbachev's ace in the hole. In the final unity
deal, he can extract economic concessions from the Germans."
   Signs of such a potential trade-off were sprinkled through
an otherwise negative Soviet performance at the unity talks,
which are formally called the "Two-Plus-Four" negotiations.
Shortly before laying down strong private objections to
German membership in the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
and making other demands, Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze held a long, cordial meeting with West German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl to discuss bilateral relations,
including economic ties.
   Mr. Shevardnadze said he and Mr. Kohl had "noted that the
potential for cooperation between our two countries is as yet
not fully exhausted. There are great reserves. There's a
great deal yet to be done, and we discussed ways of making
use of, of drawing on those reserves."
   The Soviet foreign minister also refused to restate on
West German television the strong Soviet objections to German
membership in NATO, saying only that he was optimistic a
settlement could be reached. His aides distributed his tough
remarks, including a refusal to grant the new Germany full
sovereignty, only to Soviet and East German reporters.
   Mr. Kohl has pledged that the new Germany will honor
existing trade and contract commitments between the Soviets
and East Germany, a costly proposition for Germany, because
it could require maintaining production of some items to meet
Soviet specifications, even though they can't be sold in the
West.
   Last year in Bonn, Mr. Kohl and Soviet President Mikhail
Gorbachev signed a "comprehensive economic collaboration"
stepping up trade and investment. An investment treaty has
been signed, Soviet executives are being trained in West
Germany, and German banks have set up a $1 billion credit
line for Soviet trade.
   "The Soviets realize that the united Germany has a growth
potential from which they can profit if they reform their
economy," says a German diplomat. "We've made that very clear
to them."
   But money, important as it is to the near-bankrupt
U.S.S.R., isn't the only tie that binds the two European
powers. Aware of Soviet security fears, German officials have
won U.S. support for a plan to keep NATO forces out of former
East German territory after unification. They have invited
the Red Army to remain in East German territory during a
transition period that could last seven years. The new
Germany will even pay for the troops.
   Most importantly, there is broad agreement between German
and Soviet leaders on the desirability of establishing some
new, vaguely defined Pan-European security system under the
auspices of the existing Conference on Security and
Cooperation in Europe.
   This idea, which makes U.S. officials nervous, has wide
popular appeal and is embraced to varying degrees by all
political parties in both Germanys. So far, German leaders
insist the new system would complement, not replace, NATO.
But the Soviet strategy is to build on this romantic German
notion of a Pan-European security system and eventually drive
NATO out of business by replacing it with the new security
system.
   And despite the bitter legacy of World War II, there are
historic precedents for Russian-German cooperation. "When
they weren't fighting each other, the Russians have used the
Germans as advisers for years," says Mr. Hormats. "For
centuries, there has been a love-hate relationship between
Russia and Germany."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900514-0030
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900514-0030.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Heard on the Street:
   Progressive Corp., an Insurer, Stands to Profit
   From Other Firms' Retreat From Car Coverage
   ----
   By Beatrice E. Garcia
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/14/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C2
</SO>
<CO>
   PGR AET CI TIC XRX
</CO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
HEARD ON THE STREET (HRD)
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<LP>
   Many insurers are beating a hasty retreat from the auto
insurance market. But their departure could leave the market
wide open for Progressive Corp.
   Based in Cleveland, this property/casualty insurer
specializes in providing what is delicately known as
"nonstandard" auto insurance. This isn't the coverage for the
people who drive once a week, to church on Sunday. This is
for motorists most insurers avoid -- the ones with traffic
violations, accidents, even drunk-driving convictions on
their records. It's a group that includes young drivers,
especially men in their 20s, and motorists who drive
expensive sports cars.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Major insurers such as Aetna Life &amp; Casualty, Travelers,
Cigna, Xerox's Crum &amp; Forster unit, and some regional
companies, are cutting back on the amount of auto insurance
they write or pulling out of the market altogether. With
their retreat, many drivers are left hunting for new
insurance carriers and so Progressive could end up taking on
a far better class of drivers, analysts say.
   Investors haven't fully appreciated "the change in the
nonstandard market. When that happens, this company can grow
like a weed," says Michael Takata at UBS Securities.
Progressive certainly thrived in the mid-1980s when auto
insurers racked up losses and market capacity shrank, he
recalls; the company's premiums, per-share earnings, book
value and stock prices quadrupled.
   Mr. Takata, who reiterated his buy recommendation on
Progressive recently, doesn't see the same degree of upside
potential this time. But "we could see a doubling of
(Progressive's) premiums and earnings," he says.
   The stock, which closed Friday at 38 1/8, currently sells
for just over nine times Mr. Takata's 1990 earnings estimate
of $4 a share. With annual earnings potential of $6 to $8 a
share and an uptick in the price/earnings multiple to 10 over
the next two years, he says, Progressive "would be a
$60-to-$80 stock. This is one of the few great growth stocks
in the insurance industry."
   Gerald Lewinsohn at Merrill Lynch says: "Anytime you can
buy a stock with (Progressive's earnings) record and rate of
return, and selling for a low P/E, it's a bargain."
   Insurers generally have lost money writing auto insurance
in the past decade, even though they tend to insure only what
they consider the safest drivers. At Progressive, though, net
income has grown at nearly a 15% average rate as return on
equity averaged 25.3% annually in the past 10 years -- nearly
12 points above the return of the Standard &amp; Poor's 500-stock
index.
   Progressive's first-quarter earnings report, released last
month, turned heads on Wall Street. Per-share earnings of
$1.01 far exceeded analysts' expectations of 75 cents to 80
cents. (Many firms stopped following the stock closely when
the company discontinued analyst meetings in late 1988.)
   Tom Sargent at Conning &amp; Co. has been telling clients "it
makes sense to be buying the stock now." Although the stock
has appreciated some 48% in the past 15 months, the departure
of some insurers from the market presents tremendous
potential for the company, the stock's admirers say. William
Bitterli at Northington Partners believes the shares could
sell at 50 by year end.
   Since the late 1950s Progressive has collected a huge
amount of data on high-risk drivers. It "cherry-picks among
the bad risks," one analyst says. For example, when
Progressive learned that older, married motorcyclists are
better risks than most riders of big motorcycles, it
benefited by charging them less than rivals did.
   In California, where Progressive had more than 20% of its
business, the company has adopted an extremely conservative
strategy. It set aside $34 million last year and $13.9
million in the first quarter as reserves for possible premium
refunds that might be ordered under California's auto
insurance initiative, Proposition 103. The company has also
been reducing its business in the state as much as the
current insurance laws allow. Northington's Mr. Bitterli
believes these reserves aren't likely to be needed and could
be released into future earnings.
   Progessive's long-haul trucking insurance unit, which had
a loss in 1988 after a quick start two years earlier, is
thought by analysts to have broken even in this year's first
quarter after a restructuring last year. Progressive, which
took a big hit in the 1987 market crash, today has a $2
billion portfolio that is invested largely in short-term,
high-grade securities including some adjustable-rate bonds.
Only about $240 million is in the stock market.
   ---
   Progressive
   (NYSE; Symbol: PGR)
                                                                                                       

   Business: Insurance
                                                                                                       

   Year ended Dec. 31, 1989:
   Net income: $78 million; or $2.81 a share
   (fully diluted)
                                                                                                       

   First quarter, March 31, 1990:
   Per-share earnings: $1.01 vs. 80 cents
   (fully diluted)
                                                                                                       

   Average daily trading volume:
   38,314 shares
                                                                                                       

   Common shares outstanding: 26.2 million
</TEXT>
</DOC>
