<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
05/14/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   STOCKS AND BONDS SURGED on Friday as reports of moderate
inflation and a slowing economy damped speculation that the
Fed would soon boost interest rates. Producer prices fell
0.3% in April, the second decline in two months, while retail
sales slid 0.6%, mainly due to a continued slump in auto
sales. Both declines surprised the markets.
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Dow Jones industrials closed up 63.07, at 2801.58,
near its record, in the heaviest Big Board trading this year.
Long-term Treasury bonds jumped over two points, the biggest
rally of the year. The dollar was mixed but slid 2.6% against
the yen.
   ---
   Bush and top aides tried to reassure Democrats that the
president is sincere about negotiating a deficit-cutting
accord. The administration, which sent mixed signals last
week about possibile tax increases, reiterated that budget
talks should begin tomorrow with "no preconditions."
   ---
   Some top bankers said they see clear signs of a credit
pinch in real estate, mainly due to tougher regulatory
supervision. But the bankers suggested that last week's
meeting with federal regulators could help prevent a broader
pullback in lending.
   ---
   Kidder Peabody may dismiss up to 10% of its staff as part
of a new costcutting drive, sources said. One target of the
layoffs is likely to be the investment banking division,
which the GE unit recently beefed up.
   ---
   N.V. Philips is expected to announce a big management
shake-up today that is likely to include the resignation of
president Cornelis van der Klugt. The changes are aimed at
restoring confidence in the Dutch electronics giant's sagging
stock.
   ---
   U.S. auto makers plan sizable production increases for the
third quarter, reflecting forecasts of stronger demand and
fears of a possible labor strike in September. Car output is
expected to jump 11%, while truck production is forecast to
rise 6%.
                                                                                                       

   GM's plan to nearly double the pensions of departing
chairman Roger Smith and other top executives is drawing fire
from some big holders. At least one is vowing to vote no.
   ---
   Amax isn't expected to launch a bidding war for Peabody
Holding, observers said. Amax offered $1.25 billion for the
coal company Friday but the bid was quickly topped by Hanson,
which owns 45% of Peabody. Amax's move spurred speculation of
its own vulnerability to a takeover.
   ---
   Prime Motor Inns agreed to sell a 65% stake in two
franchise systems, Howard Johnson and Ramada, to an
investment partnership for $200 million in cash and notes.
Prime is under pressure due to a soft hotel and real estate
market and a hefty debt load.
   ---
   Laventhol &amp; Horwath is facing new setbacks in the wake of
litigation and earnings woes. The No. 7 accounting firm has
lost a big Canadian affiliate, is seeing an exodus of key
personnel, and is under pressure from its main lender to sell
assets, sources said.
   ---
   Drexel's commodities trading unit disclosed details of its
debt in a court filing related to the parent company's
Chapter 11 filing in February.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 234,040,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2801.58, up 63.07; transportation 1177.45, up 16.71;
utilities 216.99, up 4.46.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3340.04, up
52.23.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 134.12, off 0.77;
spot index 135.77, off 0.73.
   Dollar: 152.65 yen, off 4.05; 1.6478 marks, up 0.0193.
</TEXT>
